Organic and metal-based electrolytes were used as hybrid redox electrolytes. A combination of the mixed redox electrolyte (1:1 in mol L−1), the tungsten-based POM anode and the hydroquinone cathode has enabled a hybrid charge storage cell with an operating voltage of 0.8 V and a specific energy density of 20 W h kg−1 [95]. A mesoporous high surface area carbon electrode enabled high gravimetric energy while possessing supercapacitor-like power handling. Anthraquinonedisulfonic acid (AQDS) was coupled with inexpensive, non-toxic iron sulfate to realize cheaper large-scale energy storage capacity [96]. The cost of redox electrolytes has been reduced further by using organic redox electrolytes. Quinone fractions (⩽\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
