Figure 6g is a revolutionary membrane-less design based on using a pair of auxiliary electrodes. Unlike ion-conducting membranes in conventional flow batteries, the anode and cathode chambers are connected through a metal wire with redox-active materials at the ends [190, 191]. The auxiliary electrodes are regenerated in situ during the charging reaction eliminating the need for external regeneration for continuous operation. This process eliminates the expensive and problematic ion-exchange membrane in a redox cell, reduces costs and increases the opportunity to use inorganic/organic, aqueous/non-aqueous redox-active liquids. A preliminary proof-of-concept demonstrated by using aqueous vanadium redox electrolytes eliminated the membrane and cut costs by incorporating ion-transfer independent redox electrolytes. A 70% cost reduction capability was demonstrated by eliminating membrane and by a potential choice of dissimilar redox electrolyte media in this design. In conventional membrane-based redox flow cells, the overall redox reaction in conventional RFB design during discharge is presented as follows:1[A]Re+[C]Ox→Discharge[A]Ox+[C]Re;EOverall=EC0-EA0\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
